<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="d7745663-0fe4-5b45-b471-08855a0d43db" activityNameId="acbaa496-bed6-4598-81d4-0c44b9829d60" parentActivityId="e118c5f4-7778-4cdf-a833-e0b7fd5a3b70" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">nitrotoluenes production, toluene nitration</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">nitrotoluenes</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">The activity ends with pure nitrotoluene isomers being ready for further transformation or transportation at the production site gate. Materials entering the process are included as well as energy uses, infrastructure and emissions.
</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the combined production of 1 kg of nitrotoluene isomers (0.584, 0.380, and 0.036 kg of o-, p-, and m-nitrotoluene, respectively), in a purified form, by the nitration of toluene.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Even though the nitration of toluene is similar to that of benzene, the methyl group on the aromatic ring increases the ease of oxidation, and thus, leading to lower selectivity due to the production of undesirable by-products (Kirk, 2004). Hence, the nitration takes place at lower temperatures compared to that of benzene, such that the rate of the oxidative side reactions is minimized, which reduces the formation of dinitrotoluenes. At the same time, the lower solubility of toluene, compared to benzene, requires vigorous agitation of the reaction mixture to increase the interfacial area between the two phases.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Reaction:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">C7H8 + HNO3 → C6H4(CH3)NO2 + H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">C7H8 + 2HNO3 → C6H3CH3(NO2)2 + 2H2O, (undesirable reaction, reduced rate due to control conditions)</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">p-Nitrotoluene (C7H7NO2; CAS 99-99-0, 4-nitrotoluene, PNT, 4-nitro-1-methylbenzene) forms colourless to light yellow rhombic – bipyramidal crystals, which are soluble in most organic solvents but only slightly soluble in water (0.044 % at 30 °C). p-Nitrotoluene derivatives are used principally as intermediates for colorants and related products; for example, p-toluidine, 4-nitrobenzoic acid (by oxidation of 4-nitrotoluene with 15 % HNO3 at 175 °C), 4-amino-2-chlorotoluene (by reduction of 2-chloro-4-nitrotoluene), and 4-nitrotoluene-2-sulfonic acid, which is of great importance in forming stilbene intermediates for fluorescent whitening agents.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">In this dataset, the raw material inputs, and process-specific material exchanges, are modelled with a generic stoichiometry-based tool, using literature or estimated yields. The emissions are modelled with a default value, which is estimated  based on losses, unreacted chemicals, among others. At the same time, the energy consumption is based on data from literature sources.  Finally, the auxiliary (i.e., cooling water and infrastructure) exchanges are modelled with a default value based on industry data from literature sources.   For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Frischknecht R., Jungbluth N., Althaus H.-J., Doka G., Dones R., Heck T., Hellweg S., Hischier R., Nemecek T., Rebitzer G. and Spielmann M. (2007) Overview and Methodology. Final report ecoinvent v2.0 No. 1. Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH, retrieved from: www.ecoinvent.org.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Kim 2003: Kim S., Overcash M.: Energy in chemical manufacturing processes: gate-to-gate information for life cycle assessment. In: Journal of Chemical Technology &amp; Biotechnology vol. 78, no. 9: 995-1005(11). 2003</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">Gerald Booth: Nitro Compounds, Aromatic. Published online: 2003. In: Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Seventh Edition, 2004 Electronic Release (ed. Fiedler E., Grossmann G., Kersebohm D., Weiss G. and Witte C.). 7 th Electronic Release Edition. Wiley InterScience, New York, Online-Version under: DOI: 10.1002/14356007.a17_411</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="11">Kirk, Raymond E., Donald F. Othmer, and Charles A. Mann. "Encyclopedia of Chemical Technology." 2004.</text>
        </generalComment>
        <tag>combined production</tag>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="7846b897-7c04-4f9f-b607-2b83fcd9a74c">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RoW</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The inventory is modelled at the Global level. The main material inputs and outputs of this activity are generated with on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields.  Furthermore, the source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The dataset could also be considered as not geography-specific, and thus, valid for a broader geographical coverage.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Kim, Seungdo, and Michael Overcash "Energy in chemical manufacturing processes: gate‐to‐gate information for life cycle assessment." Journal of Chemical Technology &amp; Biotechnology: International Research in Process, Environmental &amp; Clean Technology 78.9 (2003): 995-1005.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The nitration of toluene could take place either in a batch or continues mode. In the batch mode, the toluene is fed at around 25°C into the reactor, where the nitric acid is added slowly while the mixture temperature is maintained to 25°C, through cooling, until the entire amount of acid is introduced. Subsequently, the temperature is raised slowly to 35-40°C, at which the nitration takes place while the rate of the oxidative side reactions is minimized. The reaction has a yield of around 96%, obtaining a mixture of mononitrotoluenes. The product mixture is separated, and the spend acid is reconcentrated, while the crude product is washed with dilute caustic and water. The resulting product comprise of mononitrotoluenes mixture of 55-60% wt. o-nitrotoluene, 3-4% wt. m-nitrotoluene, and 35-40% p-nitrotoluene and the separation of the isomers is achieved via combining fractional distillation and crystallization (Kirk, 2004).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Reaction:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">C7H8 + HNO3 → C6H4(CH3)NO2 + H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">C7H8 + 2HNO3 → C6H3CH3(NO2)2 + 2H2O, (undesirable reaction, reduced rate due to control conditions)</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">In this dataset, a yield of 95% was assumed, where 1 kg of nitrotoluene isomers 0.584, 0.380, and 0.036 kg of o-, p-, and m-nitrotoluene, respectively, in a purified form</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Kirk, Raymond E., Donald F. Othmer, and Charles A. Mann. "Encyclopedia of Chemical Technology." 2004.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2003-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The time period spans from the earliest year from which at least one of the input values was obtained until 2022, but overall form the most realistic picture of the production. Besides, the activity is partly generated, in terms of material inputs and outputs, based on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields, which does not expect to change over time.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data (from 2003) for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park. The values are a 5-year average of data from 2015 to 2019 published by the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. The end time period is therefore set based on the years from Gendorf reference.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure and in the comments of the exchanges.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Kim, Seungdo, and Michael Overcash "Energy in chemical manufacturing processes: gate‐to‐gate information for life cycle assessment." Journal of Chemical Technology &amp; Biotechnology: International Research in Process, Environmental &amp; Clean Technology 78.9 (2003): 995-1005.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
    <flowData>
      <intermediateExchange id="26f7b7ff-ee03-511c-85f6-91e4f49b66a9" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" variableName="RP_para" casNumber="000099-99-0" amount="1.0" isCalculatedAmount="true" mathematicalRelation="para" intermediateExchangeId="58965072-1cd7-4e84-b8cf-b9b6494cce9f" productionVolumeAmount="3487546.3568911552" productionVolumeVariableName="RP_para_PV" productionVolumeMathematicalRelation="PV_GLO*para">
        <name xml:lang="en">p-nitrotoluene</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">According Kirk (2003), the combied production output comprise of mononitrotoluenes mixture of 55-60% wt. o-nitrotoluene, 3-4% wt m-nitrotoluene, and 35-40% p-nitrotoluene. Similar values are reported in Booth (1991).

References:
Kirk, Raymond E., Donald F. Othmer, and Charles A. Mann. "Encyclopedia of Chemical Technology." 2004.
Booth, G. (1991) Nitro compounds, aromatic. In: Elvers, B., Hawkins, S. &amp; Schulz, G., eds, Ulimann7 s Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, 5th rev. Ed., Vol. A17, New York, VCH Publishers, pp. 411-455.
</comment>
