      <parameter parameterId="1293672c-00a0-4d7a-9774-01462a98ec60" amount="221000000.0" variableName="PV_GLO" mathematicalRelation="221000000" isCalculatedAmount="true" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7">
        <name xml:lang="en">annual production</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">The 1984 capacity for mononitrotoluene (all isomers) production in the Western world was ca. 200 000 t/a, as per Booth, G. (1991). 

At the same time, Dugal (2005) reports an annual US demand for the mononitrotoluene isomers with the following contribution: 62.0, 35.0, and 3.0% for the ortho-, para-, and meta-isomer, respectively. Notably, the latter values are extremely close to the yields obtained from the nitration, and thus, one may conclude that they are directly correlated. 

Finally, in SIDS Initial Assessment Report For SIAM 17 (2003), the global production volume of p-nitrotoluene was reported to amount 77,200 t/a in 2000. A country specific breakdown was reported, as follows: Western Europe 30,000 t/y, China 26,000 t/y, US 9,000 t/y, Eastern Europe 5,000 t/y, India 4,000 t/a, and South Korea 3,200 t/y.

Please note that if one re-scale the 77,200 t of p-nitrotoluene, with the 35.0% share mentioned above, could obtain the production volume for all isomers. The obtained value (220,571 t) is close to the production volume reported for 1984, and thus, the capacity increased only marginally within these 18 years period.

All of the above were used in order to calculate the regional production volume. For more information, see mathematical relation.

References:
Booth, G. (1991) Nitro compounds, aromatic. In: Elvers, B., Hawkins, S. &amp; Schulz, G., eds, Ulimann7 s Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, 5th rev. Ed., Vol. A17, New York, VCH Publishers, pp. 411-455.
Dugal, M. (2005). Nitrobenzene and Nitrotoluenes. In Kirk-Othmer Encyclopedia of Chemical Technology, (Ed.). https://doi.org/10.1002/0471238961.1409201801041109.a01.pub2
SIDS Initial Assessment Report For SIAM 17 (2003), 4-Nitrotoluene CAS N°: 99-99-0 (Srour R (2002). Mononitrotoluenes and Derivatives. Chapter A. VII.I and A. VII.PNT, Paris.). 
https://hpvchemicals.oecd.org/UI/handler.axd?id=4cdf8442-3ecb-44b8-8d66-411f4a3ce13c</comment>
      </parameter>
      <parameter parameterId="b900761b-634b-4b39-8a15-cf804d62d576" amount="-1.11022302462516E-16" mathematicalRelation="meta + ortho + para - 1.0" isCalculatedAmount="true" unitId="577e242a-461f-44a7-922c-d8e1c3d2bf45">
        <name xml:lang="en">check_balance</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">dimensionless</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Check if the yield of meta-, ortho-, and para- is equal to 1.</comment>
      </parameter>
      <parameter parameterId="728b3749-3646-4f57-812a-500d8cda54f0" amount="0.035532995" variableName="meta" unitId="577e242a-461f-44a7-922c-d8e1c3d2bf45">
        <name xml:lang="en">nitration_yield_meta</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">dimensionless</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">According Kirk (2003), the combied production output comprise of mononitrotoluenes mixture of 55-60% wt. o-nitrotoluene, 3-4% wt m-nitrotoluene, and 35-40% p-nitrotoluene. Similar values are reported in Booth (1991).

References:
Kirk, Raymond E., Donald F. Othmer, and Charles A. Mann. "Encyclopedia of Chemical Technology." 2004.
Booth, G. (1991) Nitro compounds, aromatic. In: Elvers, B., Hawkins, S. &amp; Schulz, G., eds, Ulimann7 s Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, 5th rev. Ed., Vol. A17, New York, VCH Publishers, pp. 411-455.
</comment>
      </parameter>
      <parameter parameterId="d28615b7-edcb-47f8-b196-4ea1081abc7e" amount="0.583756345" variableName="ortho" unitId="577e242a-461f-44a7-922c-d8e1c3d2bf45">
        <name xml:lang="en">nitration_yield_ortho</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">dimensionless</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">According Kirk (2003), the combied production output comprise of mononitrotoluenes mixture of 55-60% wt. o-nitrotoluene, 3-4% wt m-nitrotoluene, and 35-40% p-nitrotoluene. Similar values are reported in Booth (1991).

References:
Kirk, Raymond E., Donald F. Othmer, and Charles A. Mann. "Encyclopedia of Chemical Technology." 2004.
Booth, G. (1991) Nitro compounds, aromatic. In: Elvers, B., Hawkins, S. &amp; Schulz, G., eds, Ulimann7 s Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, 5th rev. Ed., Vol. A17, New York, VCH Publishers, pp. 411-455.
</comment>
      </parameter>
      <parameter parameterId="91e630ad-26a5-4100-b4c8-681d7e8cd3de" amount="0.38071066" variableName="para" unitId="577e242a-461f-44a7-922c-d8e1c3d2bf45">
        <name xml:lang="en">nitration_yield_para</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">dimensionless</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">According Kirk (2003), the combied production output comprise of mononitrotoluenes mixture of 55-60% wt. o-nitrotoluene, 3-4% wt m-nitrotoluene, and 35-40% p-nitrotoluene. Similar values are reported in Booth (1991).

References:
Kirk, Raymond E., Donald F. Othmer, and Charles A. Mann. "Encyclopedia of Chemical Technology." 2004.
Booth, G. (1991) Nitro compounds, aromatic. In: Elvers, B., Hawkins, S. &amp; Schulz, G., eds, Ulimann7 s Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, 5th rev. Ed., Vol. A17, New York, VCH Publishers, pp. 411-455.
